</ol>
<p><a name="External_links" id="External_links"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=ATA_over_Ethernet&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: External links">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">External links</span></h2>
<ul>
<li>Articles:
<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.linuxjournal.com/article/8149" class="external text" title="http://www.linuxjournal.com/article/8149" rel="nofollow">ATA Over Ethernet: Putting Hard Drives on the LAN</a> — <a href="/wiki/Linux_Journal" title="Linux Journal">Linux Journal</a> (28 April 2005)</li>
<li><a href="http://linuxdevices.com/news/NS3189760067.html" class="external text" title="http://linuxdevices.com/news/NS3189760067.html" rel="nofollow">ATA-over-Ethernet enables low-cost Linux-oriented SAN</a> — LinuxDevices.com (23 June 2004)</li>
<li><a href="http://www.linux-mag.com/id/2028/" class="external text" title="http://www.linux-mag.com/id/2028/" rel="nofollow">The ATA over Ethernet (AoE) Protocol</a> — <a href="/wiki/Linux_Magazine" title="Linux Magazine">Linux Magazine</a> (<span class="mw-formatted-date" title="2005-06-15"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="06-15"><a href="/wiki/June_15" title="June 15">June 15</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/2005" title="2005">2005</a></span>)</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Protocol:
<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.coraid.com/site/co-pdfs/AoEr10.pdf" class="external text" title="http://www.coraid.com/site/co-pdfs/AoEr10.pdf" rel="nofollow">AoE protocol description</a> (<a href="/wiki/Portable_Document_Format" title="Portable Document Format">PDF</a> file)</li>
<li><a href="http://www.coraid.com/s.nl/sc.12/category.1120/.f" class="external text" title="http://www.coraid.com/s.nl/sc.12/category.1120/.f" rel="nofollow">AoE protocol specification</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Implementations and Tools:
<ul>
<li><a href="http://sourceforge.net/projects/aoetools/" class="external text" title="http://sourceforge.net/projects/aoetools/" rel="nofollow">ATA Over Ethernet Tools and vblade</a> vblade is an AoE target that runs in userspace, and kvblade is an alpha in-kernel AoE target</li>
<li><a href="http://lpk.com.price.ru/~lelik/AoE/" class="external text" title="http://lpk.com.price.ru/~lelik/AoE/" rel="nofollow">vblade, implemented as a kernel module</a> this is faster than the userspace vblade</li>
<li><a href="http://pi.nxs.se/~wowie/qaoed.tgz/" class="external text" title="http://pi.nxs.se/~wowie/qaoed.tgz/" rel="nofollow">qaoed - Mulithreaded ATA over Ethernet storage target</a> Runs in userspace</li>
<li><a href="http://code.google.com/p/aoeserver/" class="external text" title="http://code.google.com/p/aoeserver/" rel="nofollow">Aoeserver - Mulithreaded ATA over Ethernet storage target</a> Implemented as a kernel module</li>
<li><a href="http://code.google.com/p/ggaoed/" class="external text" title="http://code.google.com/p/ggaoed/" rel="nofollow">ggaoed</a> - AoE target implementation for Linux</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Live CD:
<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.lbserver.org/aoe/" class="external text" title="http://www.lbserver.org/aoe/" rel="nofollow">Slax Frodo with vblade and ATA Over Ethernet Tools</a> this is useful for testing and backup</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>HowTos:
<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.howtoforge.com/ata_over_ethernet_debian_etch" class="external text" title="http://www.howtoforge.com/ata_over_ethernet_debian_etch" rel="nofollow">Using ATA Over Ethernet On Debian Etch</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>


